{"text": "the energy levels (Landau magnetism) or with the spins (Pauly magnetism). De\n\nnitions:\n\n\u000fDiamagnetic System - in a magnetic\n\neld, the system energy increases.\n\n\u000fParamagnetic System - in a magnetic\n\neld, the system energy decreases.\n\nThe Aharonov Bohm geometry provides the simplest example for magnetic response. If we place one electron in a ring,\n\nand add a weak magnetic \rux, the system energy increases. Accordingly we say that the response is \"diamagnetic\".\n\nThe electron cannot \"get rid\" of its kinetic energy, because of the quantization of the momentum.\n\n225\n\n= = = = = = [45.5] Dirac Monopoles\n\nYet another consequence of the \"Aharonov Bohm\" e\u000bect is the quantization of the magnetic charge. Dirac has claimed\n\nthat if magnetic monopoles exist, then there must be an elementary magnetic charge. The formal argument can be\n\nphrased as follows: If a magnetic monopole exists, it creates a vector potential\n\neld in space ( A(x)). The e\u000bect of the\n\neld of the monopole on an electron close by is given by the line integralH~A\u0001d~ r. We can evaluate the integral by\n\ncalculating the magnetic \rux \b through a Stokes surface. The result should not depend on the choice of the surface,\n\notherwise the phase is not be well de\n\nned. In particular we can choose Stokes surfaces that pass above and below the\n\nmonopole, and deduce that the phase di\u000berence \u001e=e\b=~cshould be zero modulo 2 \u0019. Hence the \rux \b should be an\n\ninteger multiple of 2 \u0019~c=e. Using \"Gauss law\" we conclude that the monopole must have a magnetic charge that is\n\nquantized in units of ~c=2e.\n\nDirac's original reasoning was somewhat more constructive. Let us assume that a magnetic monopole exist. The\n\nmagnetic\n\neld that would be created by this monopole would be like that of a tip of a solenoid. But we have to\n\nexclude the region in space where we have the magnetic \rux that goes through the solenoid.", "embe